This nerve innervates the muscles of mastication responsible for opening and closing the mouth and allows for sensation from the face including the mouth. Option D (parasympathetic component only) is incorrect as the parasympathetic nervous system is responsible for regulating activities such as digestion and urination, and is not involved in the motor and sensory function of the trigeminal nerve.

The inability to open mouth wide or completely chew suggests damage to the mandibular nerve, which has both voluntary motor and sensory components. Sensory component only would result in numbness or altered sensation, voluntary motor component only would result in weakness or paralysis of the muscles. Parasympathetic component only would affect autonomic functions such as tear production or salivation.
